WEBVTT

00:02.303 --> 00:04.838
[ Upbeat music plays ]

00:04.838 --> 00:14.815
♪♪

00:14.815 --> 00:17.218
♪♪

00:23.191 --> 00:30.231
♪♪

00:30.231 --> 00:31.699
Huh?

00:31.699 --> 00:33.667
[ Trap clacks ]
Aah!

00:33.667 --> 00:36.337
Hmm. "Hit the rat
three times to get in."

00:36.337 --> 00:38.639
[ Squeak! Squeak! Squeak! ]

00:38.639 --> 00:40.174
Dad, you made it!

00:40.174 --> 00:41.409
Uh, yeah.

00:41.409 --> 00:43.811
There's food, right?

00:43.811 --> 00:46.280
Together:
Happy Vermin Man Day!

00:46.280 --> 00:47.415
Happy what, now?

00:47.415 --> 00:48.516
Together:
Grandpa Frankie!

00:48.516 --> 00:49.650
Oh, hey, kids.

00:49.650 --> 00:51.519
Uh...Nicole,
these are for you.

00:51.519 --> 00:52.820
Oh. Thank you.

00:52.820 --> 00:54.622
"You'll always be alive
in our hearts...

00:54.622 --> 00:56.624
Great-Aunt Petunia."

00:56.624 --> 00:59.360
Sorry. I couldn't find one
that said "Nicole."

00:59.360 --> 01:01.028
Especially not
in the dark.

01:01.028 --> 01:02.396
Who invited him?

01:02.396 --> 01:04.432
Me! It's a proper
family get-together.

01:04.432 --> 01:06.534
You're late, Dad.
You almost missed the song.

01:06.534 --> 01:07.868
Well, at least
I'm here now.

01:07.868 --> 01:09.670
[ Whispering ]
And if anyone asks,

01:09.670 --> 01:12.039
I was also here Thursday night
between 8:00 and 11:00.

01:12.039 --> 01:15.676
[ Laughter ]

01:15.676 --> 01:20.013
Come on, kids. All together now
for the Vermin Man song!

01:20.013 --> 01:22.150
♪ Here he comes,
the Vermin Man ♪

01:22.150 --> 01:25.786
♪ He's always ready
with a trick or a scam ♪

01:25.786 --> 01:27.855
♪ With his one black eye
and his pointed nose ♪

01:27.855 --> 01:29.790
♪ And an outfit
straight from '80s cop shows ♪

01:29.790 --> 01:31.592
♪ He's a liar and a rogue
and a sponger and a thief ♪

01:31.592 --> 01:35.529
♪ He'll take away your happiness
and fill you full of grief ♪

01:35.529 --> 01:37.665
♪ Here he comes,
the Vermin Man ♪

01:37.665 --> 01:40.033
♪ He's always ready
with a trick or a scam ♪

01:40.033 --> 01:41.302
[ Boing! Boing! Boing! ]

01:41.302 --> 01:43.271
♪ He's a no-good husband
and a deadbeat dad ♪

01:43.271 --> 01:45.239
♪ If he disappeared for good,
then we'd all be glad ♪

01:45.239 --> 01:47.074
♪ His face is gross,
his manner is brash ♪

01:47.074 --> 01:48.409
♪ If you split him
down the middle ♪

01:48.409 --> 01:51.078
♪ All you'll find is trash

01:51.078 --> 01:53.080
♪ Here he comes,
the Vermin Man ♪

01:53.080 --> 01:55.649
♪ He's always ready
with a trick or a scam ♪

01:55.649 --> 01:57.785
Where's the candy?
There isn't any.

01:57.785 --> 01:59.420
Just garbage to symbolize

01:59.420 --> 02:02.790
how rotten the Vermin Man is
on the inside.

02:02.790 --> 02:04.792
♪ Got a hole for a soul
and a heart like a knife ♪

02:04.792 --> 02:06.694
♪ He let down
his child and wife ♪

02:06.694 --> 02:08.596
♪ Never, ever marry him,
he'll ruin your life ♪

02:08.596 --> 02:12.233
♪ The Vermin Man

02:12.233 --> 02:17.037
♪ He's always ready with a trick
or a lie or a con or a hustle ♪

02:17.037 --> 02:20.708
♪ Or a hoax or a fraud
or a racket or a sham ♪

02:20.708 --> 02:24.345
♪ Or a diddle or a fiddle
or a scaaaam ♪

02:24.345 --> 02:27.181
[ Explosion ]

02:29.116 --> 02:30.384
Well, it wasn't about me.

02:30.384 --> 02:31.719
Yeah, I know.
I get the hint.

02:31.719 --> 02:32.986
Don't worry, Dad.

02:32.986 --> 02:34.788
The Vermin Man
isn't about you.

02:34.788 --> 02:36.824
It's a tradition
as old as time.

02:36.824 --> 02:39.893
Mom said it started when the
Pilgrims first came to this land

02:39.893 --> 02:42.630
and they were all abandoned
by their deadbeat father.

02:42.630 --> 02:44.031
You know -- the British.

02:44.031 --> 02:45.266
Mm, no, son.

02:45.266 --> 02:48.035
I think it was probably
invented by your mom.

02:48.035 --> 02:50.070
'Cause she can't stand me.
-I invented it

02:50.070 --> 02:51.972
to distract our son
from remembering

02:51.972 --> 02:54.107
the date
you walked out on us...

02:54.107 --> 02:56.510
and, yes,
because I can't stand you.

02:56.510 --> 02:58.145
I'm sorry, Richard.

02:58.145 --> 02:59.713
I shouldn't have come.

02:59.713 --> 03:02.149
I can't make up
for what I've done to you.

03:02.149 --> 03:04.385
I've missed too much.

03:04.385 --> 03:07.455
♪♪

03:07.455 --> 03:08.756
Has he gone?

03:08.756 --> 03:11.392
The lousy bum
stole my wallet!

03:11.392 --> 03:13.627
♪♪

03:13.627 --> 03:15.596
Oh, this is bad.

03:15.596 --> 03:17.030
What can we do
to cheer him up?

03:17.030 --> 03:18.131
Oh, I know!

03:18.131 --> 03:20.301
Dad rock.
[ Rock music plays ]

03:20.301 --> 03:23.671
♪ I'm gonna rock you till you
feel the rock 'n' roll ♪

03:23.671 --> 03:26.540
♪ Rock around the rock
that is made out of rock ♪

03:26.540 --> 03:29.877
♪ I'm gonna rock it back and
forth like a rocking horse ♪

03:29.877 --> 03:33.781
♪ Gonna quench your thirst
with some rock on the rocks ♪

03:33.781 --> 03:37.117
Wow. There's a lot of promise
of rocking, but...

03:37.117 --> 03:39.219
Yeah, it's like having someone
take you around a theme park

03:39.219 --> 03:40.854
telling you how much fun
you're gonna have,

03:40.854 --> 03:42.490
but you never get
to go on the rides.

03:42.490 --> 03:44.492
Well, he's kind of rocking.

03:44.492 --> 03:45.826
[ Rock music continues ]

03:45.826 --> 03:48.128
Just encourage him
with a bit of Dad dancing.

03:48.128 --> 03:49.463
[ Snap! ]

03:49.463 --> 03:52.733
♪♪

03:52.733 --> 03:54.835
[ Crying ]
What's wrong?

03:54.835 --> 03:57.938
That's the music
from my dad's generation.

03:57.938 --> 04:00.541
♪ We'll follow you into the -- ♪

04:00.541 --> 04:02.610
[ Heavy metal music plays ]

04:02.610 --> 04:04.545
[ Grunge music plays ]

04:04.545 --> 04:08.115
[ Dance music plays ]
♪ Whoa-oh-oh, whoa-oh-oh, whoa ♪

04:08.115 --> 04:10.017
♪ Whoa-oh-oh, oh-oh-oh ♪
[ Whimpers ]

04:10.017 --> 04:13.020
[ Music stops ]
Faker.

04:13.020 --> 04:15.756
You only bought the T-shirts
for the cool bands, didn't you?

04:15.756 --> 04:18.091
Mm-hmm.
Come on.
Let's go to Joyful Burger.

04:18.091 --> 04:21.295
For once, you've got
our permission to comfort eat.

04:22.796 --> 04:23.997
How about a joke?

04:23.997 --> 04:25.399
Knock, knock?
Dad?!

04:25.399 --> 04:26.500
What? No.

04:26.500 --> 04:27.735
[ Wailing ]

04:27.735 --> 04:30.471
Larry:
So, that's one large fries.

04:30.471 --> 04:32.873
I mean,
I don't have any real...

04:32.873 --> 04:34.542
Beef.
...with my dad.

04:34.542 --> 04:36.009
Sure, he's made mis--
Steaks.

04:36.009 --> 04:38.178
But now there's
too much time to...
Ketchup.

04:38.178 --> 04:40.514
And all this
has left me in a...
Bit of a pickle.

04:40.514 --> 04:41.815
While he's gone on
to make a...

04:41.815 --> 04:43.351
Hash brown.
...of his life.

04:43.351 --> 04:44.585
It's so hard
when a parent...

04:44.585 --> 04:45.619
Desserts.
...you.

04:45.619 --> 04:46.854
And now I...
Doughnut.

04:46.854 --> 04:47.888
...know what to do.

04:47.888 --> 04:49.089
Every night...
Ice scream.

04:49.089 --> 04:49.957
...inside.

04:49.957 --> 04:51.158
I just feel so...
Waffle.

04:51.158 --> 04:52.793
I ought to tell him
how I feel,

04:52.793 --> 04:54.227
but I guess
I'm too much of a...

04:54.227 --> 04:56.229
Boneless chicken!

04:56.229 --> 05:00.534
And comfort eating is not
going to make me any happier.

05:00.534 --> 05:02.069
[ Laughs, chomps ]

05:02.069 --> 05:03.671
[ Laughs, chomps ]

05:03.671 --> 05:05.038
[ Laughs, chomps ]

05:05.038 --> 05:06.474
This doesn't look good
to me.

05:06.474 --> 05:08.509
I don't think anyone would enjoy
the sight of a grown man

05:08.509 --> 05:11.144
smearing burger meat into
his face in a kid's ball pit.

05:11.144 --> 05:13.814
Yep. Even in Japan,
that's pretty niche.

05:13.814 --> 05:16.717
[ Screaming ]

05:16.717 --> 05:18.752
Hmm.

05:18.752 --> 05:20.354
Isn't all
this eating dangerous?

05:20.354 --> 05:22.790
Nah, this is Richard Watterson.
He can take it.

05:22.790 --> 05:24.057
[ Sirens wailing ]

05:24.057 --> 05:26.193
Yeah, I was more worried
about the staff.

05:26.193 --> 05:29.430
It was like shoveling French
fries down an elevator shaft.

05:29.430 --> 05:33.133
Well. Now my brain
and my stomach are sad.

05:33.133 --> 05:34.735
Darwin:
I've got an idea!

05:34.735 --> 05:36.069
♪♪

05:36.069 --> 05:38.271
This is what I do
when I feel blue.

05:38.271 --> 05:41.308
I look at the clouds and
see that even the darkest ones

05:41.308 --> 05:42.576
eventually drift away.

05:42.576 --> 05:44.512
And it's fun
'cause they make shapes.

05:44.512 --> 05:45.513
Like that one.

05:45.513 --> 05:46.880
It looks like a hat.

05:46.880 --> 05:48.716
A hat like my father's.

05:48.716 --> 05:51.719
-Uh, sure.
-How about that one?

05:51.719 --> 05:53.387
Anais:
It's like a horseshoe.

05:53.387 --> 05:54.622
Shoes are for walking.

05:54.622 --> 05:56.990
Like he walked out on me.
[ Groans ]

05:56.990 --> 05:58.759
Well,
how about that one?

05:58.759 --> 05:59.960
It looks like a...uh...

05:59.960 --> 06:02.062
Oh.
Looks like a popsicle.

06:02.062 --> 06:04.798
Oh.
Uh...I-I guess.

06:04.798 --> 06:07.000
Popsicles are cold
like the Arctic Ocean.

06:07.000 --> 06:09.302
And that's cold because it's got
lots of icebergs in it.

06:09.302 --> 06:10.871
That's why it's dangerous
for ships.

06:10.871 --> 06:12.272
Because icebergs sink ships.

06:12.272 --> 06:14.708
And what's the first thing
to leave a sinking ship?

06:14.708 --> 06:15.909
A rat.

06:15.909 --> 06:17.511
Together: [ Groan ]

06:17.511 --> 06:18.879
And rats
are covered in fleas.

06:18.879 --> 06:20.548
Just like my father
"flea'd" from me.

06:20.548 --> 06:23.350
Yeah, we got it.
You could have stopped at "rat."

06:23.350 --> 06:24.752
Gumball: I just.
I...

06:24.752 --> 06:26.186
I don't know
what else to do.

06:26.186 --> 06:28.822
Dad, you've just got to talk
to Grandpa Frankie about it.

06:28.822 --> 06:30.190
[ Groans ]
There's no point.

06:30.190 --> 06:31.459
He's just a con man.

06:31.459 --> 06:34.094
The best I can hope for is
that the next time I see him,

06:34.094 --> 06:36.263
he doesn't hustle me
out of $700

06:36.263 --> 06:38.832
with that ball-and-cups
trick...again.

06:38.832 --> 06:41.669
These cups and this ball
are worth $2,000.

06:41.669 --> 06:44.472
But as you're my son, I'll let
you have 'em for $700!

06:44.472 --> 06:45.773
[ Gasps ]

06:45.773 --> 06:47.908
[ Groans ] I don't know
what to say to him.

06:47.908 --> 06:50.310
I can't put it into words.

06:50.310 --> 06:51.712
Would it help to sing it?

06:51.712 --> 06:54.748
You know what?
I think maybe it would.

06:54.748 --> 06:56.416
[ Breathes deeply ]

06:56.416 --> 06:59.252
[ Serene piano music plays ]

06:59.252 --> 07:01.154
[ Screams ]

07:01.154 --> 07:02.790
[ Cackling ]

07:02.790 --> 07:04.391
[ Muttering ]

07:04.391 --> 07:05.793
[ Crying ]

07:05.793 --> 07:07.027
Brrreeeueew!

07:07.027 --> 07:08.696
Was that clear?
Together: Uh...

07:08.696 --> 07:10.263
-Uh-huh.
-Uh-huh.

07:10.263 --> 07:12.199
But that doesn't mean
you can't fix...

07:12.199 --> 07:15.235
whatever that was...
between you.

07:15.235 --> 07:18.138
I would need
to make a time machine.
Why?

07:18.138 --> 07:19.940
Because if I invented
a time machine,

07:19.940 --> 07:23.376
my dad would be
really proud of me.

07:23.376 --> 07:24.812
It's too late, anyway.

07:24.812 --> 07:26.780
I'll never get
those years back.

07:26.780 --> 07:27.948
[ Sobbing ]

07:27.948 --> 07:29.617
No. Not true.

07:29.617 --> 07:31.051
You can't travel
back in time

07:31.051 --> 07:33.020
and experience
the things you guys missed,

07:33.020 --> 07:35.188
but you can travel forward
in time

07:35.188 --> 07:37.390
and fix the things
that are yet to come.

07:37.390 --> 07:39.893
Because the future
starts now.

07:39.893 --> 07:41.194
[ Gasp ]

07:41.194 --> 07:42.596
Huh. That was really good,
wasn't it?

07:42.596 --> 07:44.231
[ Chuckles ]
Kind of surprised myself there.

07:44.231 --> 07:46.266
I was like,
"The future starts now."

07:46.266 --> 07:47.935
Bam! Nailed it.
[ Chuckles ]

07:47.935 --> 07:50.671
The future starts now...

07:50.671 --> 07:52.239
Now.

07:52.239 --> 07:53.473
Now.

07:53.473 --> 07:54.942
[ Imitates explosion ]

07:54.942 --> 07:56.577
[ Imitates explosion ]

07:56.577 --> 07:57.911
[ Imitates explosion ]

07:57.911 --> 07:59.179
[ Imitates explosion ]
Can we just --

07:59.179 --> 08:00.748
Yeah. Sorry.
Let's just get on with it.

08:00.748 --> 08:02.550
[ Alarm blaring in distance ]

08:02.550 --> 08:03.717
[ Groans ]

08:03.717 --> 08:04.918
Oh.
There you are.

08:04.918 --> 08:06.053
So, here's the plan.

08:06.053 --> 08:07.354
You guys go through
everything

08:07.354 --> 08:08.622
a father and son
should have shared,

08:08.622 --> 08:09.690
but, like, really fast.

08:09.690 --> 08:11.191
Three, two, one.
Go!

08:11.191 --> 08:13.493
So, uh...
where do we start?

08:13.493 --> 08:16.229
How about
a piggyback ride?
Okay.

08:16.229 --> 08:18.231
That's as good
a place as -- Aah!

08:18.231 --> 08:19.633
[ Sentimental music plays ]

08:19.633 --> 08:21.134
You ready, champ?

08:21.134 --> 08:22.335
Yeah!

08:23.303 --> 08:25.172
[ Laughs ]
Well done, son!

08:25.172 --> 08:27.040
And now we run!
Why?

08:27.040 --> 08:29.877
Because, technically,
that's not our ball.

08:29.877 --> 08:31.411
Huh?

08:31.411 --> 08:32.946
[ Groans ]

08:32.946 --> 08:34.615
[ Grunts ]
Ow!

08:34.615 --> 08:36.950
Frankie: This priceless
heirloom was passed down

08:36.950 --> 08:40.153
from grandfather to father,
and from father to son.

08:40.153 --> 08:43.691
And it was passed down from
that son's second-story window

08:43.691 --> 08:46.193
by my former cellmate to me.

08:46.193 --> 08:48.629
And now it's yours.

08:48.629 --> 08:50.631
I...don't know
what to say.

08:50.631 --> 08:52.833
Good.
'Cause anything you do say

08:52.833 --> 08:54.467
might be held against you
in court.

08:54.467 --> 08:56.336
What?
[ Pants, grunts ]

08:56.336 --> 08:58.171
[ Sirens blaring ]
Officer:
Okay, go, go, go, go, go!

08:58.171 --> 09:00.273
Now make sure
you don't forget

09:00.273 --> 09:01.975
the little bit
under your chin.

09:01.975 --> 09:03.310
[ Grunts ]

09:03.310 --> 09:04.511
Very good.

09:04.511 --> 09:05.779
Now the second one.

09:05.779 --> 09:07.447
[ Straining ]

09:07.447 --> 09:08.782
And now the third.

09:08.782 --> 09:10.984
[ Whimpering ]
Great.

09:10.984 --> 09:12.152
Now you just have
to slide

09:12.152 --> 09:14.287
down the drain pipe
and run.

09:14.287 --> 09:15.789
[ Dogs barking ]

09:15.789 --> 09:18.291
[ Screaming ]

09:18.291 --> 09:19.426
[ Sighs ]

09:19.426 --> 09:21.795
Now, first,
you release the hand brake.

09:21.795 --> 09:24.031
Now gently slip it
into drive.

09:24.031 --> 09:26.033
Aah!
Agh, I don't like it, Dad!

09:26.033 --> 09:28.669
It's perfectly normal
to be nervous

09:28.669 --> 09:30.103
your first time driving...

09:30.103 --> 09:31.271
a getaway car.

09:31.271 --> 09:32.940
I'm sorry.
I can't do this!

09:32.940 --> 09:34.141
[ Alarms blaring ]

09:34.141 --> 09:35.709
Hey, wait!
Where are you going?!

09:35.709 --> 09:37.911
[ Siren chirps ]

09:37.911 --> 09:40.513
Oh.
Now reel it in, son.

09:40.513 --> 09:41.915
Nice and easy.

09:41.915 --> 09:43.784
Ha ha ha ha!

09:43.784 --> 09:44.852
[ Horn honking ]

09:44.852 --> 09:46.654
Okay, I think
that's enough.

09:46.654 --> 09:48.689
What?
What did I do wrong?!

09:48.689 --> 09:50.290
It's no good.

09:50.290 --> 09:53.226
I thought this would be
a father-and-son bonding thing.

09:53.226 --> 09:55.295
You know?
We'd talk about life.

09:55.295 --> 09:57.464
Oh, that's cool.
Let's do that now.

09:57.464 --> 09:59.833
[ Sniffles ]
That would be nice.

09:59.833 --> 10:01.869
Okay, so, "life."

10:01.869 --> 10:03.637
Life is like 15, 20 years,

10:03.637 --> 10:05.773
but you can be out in 10
with good behavior.

10:05.773 --> 10:07.908
Oh, forget it!

10:07.908 --> 10:09.142
Oh, look, son.

10:09.142 --> 10:10.543
You know what I'm like.

10:10.543 --> 10:12.012
I'm the Vermin Man.

10:12.012 --> 10:13.681
I'm no role model.

10:13.681 --> 10:16.616
I'm more of a parole model.
[ Chuckles ]

10:16.616 --> 10:18.318
Eugh.
Oh.

10:18.318 --> 10:20.954
Look, I didn't want you
to turn out like me.

10:20.954 --> 10:22.022
And I was right.

10:22.022 --> 10:24.191
Look at you.
You turned out great.

10:24.191 --> 10:25.993
And your kids love you.

10:25.993 --> 10:28.929
I didn't start off
as a good father.

10:28.929 --> 10:30.197
But your kids...

10:30.197 --> 10:32.132
they see you as better
than you are,

10:32.132 --> 10:34.267
so every day,
you bust your chops

10:34.267 --> 10:36.036
and try to live up to that.

10:36.036 --> 10:38.538
It's too late for me.

10:38.538 --> 10:40.307
No. Not true.

10:40.307 --> 10:42.309
You know what my kids
taught me today?

10:42.309 --> 10:44.812
The future starts now.

10:44.812 --> 10:46.546
[ Sniffles ]
Yeah.

10:46.546 --> 10:49.750
I'm sorry, son.

10:49.750 --> 10:51.551
I'm sorry, too.

10:51.551 --> 10:54.154
[ Voice breaking ] You've got
nothing to apologize for.

10:54.154 --> 10:55.488
Yes, I do.

10:55.488 --> 10:57.557
I stole your wallet.

10:57.557 --> 11:00.160
That's my boy.

11:00.160 --> 11:02.195
And don't worry.
It's not mine anyway.

11:06.499 --> 11:16.509
♪♪

11:16.509 --> 11:26.553
♪♪

11:26.553 --> 11:35.395
♪♪
